    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "The originalist approach to constitutional interpretation is fundamentally incapable of addressing modern civil rights issues because it is rooted in the historical context of the 18th century, which is vastly different from today's society. The founders could not have envisioned the complexities of modern life, such as issues related to gender equality, LGBTQ+ rights, and reproductive freedom. By adhering strictly to the original text and intent of the Constitution, originalism fails to recognize the evolving nature of human rights and the need for the law to adapt to contemporary values and social progress. Substantive due process, on the other hand, allows the Constitution to be a living document that can grow and change with society, ensuring that fundamental human rights are protected even as new challenges arise. It is this flexibility and responsiveness to the needs of the people that make substantive due process a vital tool for advancing civil rights and personal liberties in our modern world. Originalism, by contrast, is an outdated and rigid framework that cannot keep pace with the demands of a diverse and evolving society. It is a relic of a bygone era that hinders progress and perpetuates injustice by refusing to acknowledge the inherent dignity and equality of all individuals. Substantive due process is not just a legal principle; it is a",
